===Glyph origin===
{{Han etym}}
{{Han compound|金|壽|t1=metal|c1=s|c2=p|ls=psc}}. Historical forms for this character feature large amounts of various decorative components, including {{och-l|*皿|gloss=container, crucible, or mould}}, {{och-l|*火|gloss=fire}}, {{och-l|*寸|gloss=hand}}, or {{och-l|*𦦡}} = {{och-l|*𦥑|two hands}} + {{och-l|*鬲|gloss=cauldron, container}}, etc., indicating metal-casting. The phonetic value were signified by the optional component {{och-l|*𠃬}}, which also appeared in {{och-l|壽}}.

===Etymology===
Connected by {{zh-ref|Schuessler (2007)}} to {{och-l|注|to pour}}, though the Baxter-Sagart reconstruction makes this phonetically suspect. Note, however, stronger phonetic similarities to {{cog|my|တူး|t=to be burnt, scorched}}.

